         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">... twenty(?) .... In (this way) it [=merit] can be obtained from the organic elements. In which</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a1 #a2 #a3 #a4 #a5 #b1 #b2 #b3 #b4 #b5"><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:tamai2014"/><citedRange>388-389</citedRange></bibl></seg><seg><bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1986"/><citedRange>100-102</citedRange></bibl></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">way (can it be obtained from) the inorganic (elements)? In this way, from [the element] earth [and] from the atoms of the earth, self-discipline may be</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">obtained: From all green, (white(?) [and] black(?)) seeds, whatever seeds there are near or far,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">from all [of them] self-discipline can be obtained. (Thus) it can be obtained from (all organic [and] inor)ganic elements. Just as</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">the organic [and] inorganic (elements have neither measure nor number), just so the merit of ordination has</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">neither measure nor number. This (for you is the second effect) of ordin(ation). [3.] (Fruition [= requital of deeds]), what is [this]? When you let come to fruition this merit for all goods of happiness in the saṃsāra,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(you will obtain(?) all) this. All [your] desires [such as] the dignity of Indra, the dignity of a cakravartin king,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">and so on(will be fulfilled for you. But if) you let this [=merit] come to fruition with a mind filled with [life-]weariness for release from the saṃsāra,</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[then] (you will be released from the) saṃsāra by [one of] three paths: ([the path] of the) Buddha, of the Pratyekabuddha [and] of the Arhat.</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">To whatever .... (you will turn to, release from the saṃsāra will be) yours. This for you is the thi(rd) effect of ordination.</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="philcomment" subtype="Transcription">The supplementation and commentaries follow <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1986"/><citedRange>30, 142</citedRange></bibl>.</note><note type="remarks">According to <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1986"/></bibl>: iv-v this ms. comes either from Qizil or from Tumšuq.</note><note type="remarks">From this leaf 2 fragments are preserved: one from the left side of the leaf to the string hole, consisting of 2 pieces and about 7 cm wide, and the right half of of the leaf, about 14 cm wide.</note><note type="remarks">The original ms. was 29 cm wide and 5.6 cm high, with the string hole 6.5 cm from the left margin. It was written by at least three hands: scribe 1, a beautiful, delicate script, from leaf 1 to 11 a1; scribe 2, distinguished by a number of orthographical idiosyncrasies/errors, from leaf 11 a1 to and including 19; scribe 3 from leaf 20 to end. The final leaves A and B <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1123"/> and <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-tht1124"/> may have been written either by scribe 2 or a fourth hand. Cf. <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1986"/></bibl>: v, 2, 6</note><note type="remarks">This leaf is in hand 3.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="lingcomment">Instead of <hi>ikä</hi>, which would have to be supplemented to <hi>ikäṃ</hi>, one could also read <hi>itä</hi> or <hi>isä</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 14 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment"><hi>paramanuntameṃ</hi> for <hi>paramānuntameṃ</hi>; <hi>saṃvār</hi> for <hi>saṃvar</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment"><hi>onolmeṃtsana</hi>: for a possible further supplementation cf. line a 1.</note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 7 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="lingcomment">With the help of <hi>(mo)tärcce</hi> (<ref type="ms" target="txt:m-ioltoch106"/> b5), = Skt. <hi>harita</hi>, the meaning of <hi>motarcca(na)</hi>, Pl. Fem. of an adjective, can be identified as ‘green’ (for more detail see <bibl><title corresp="ref:schmidtkt1984"/><citedRange>152</citedRange></bibl>). In TA there is <hi>motarci</hi> (Nom.Sg.Fem.), which, according to <bibl><title corresp="ref:krauseandthomas1964"/><citedRange>127</citedRange></bibl>, denotes a colour that is probably dark, but otherwise unidentifiable. Etymologically, this colour adjective must be connected to Slavic <hi>*modrъ</hi> ‘blue’ (Czech <hi>modrý</hi>, etc.).</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 8 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#a3 #a4" type="lingcomment"><hi>etsuwai elauke wat</hi> ‘near or far’.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="lingcomment"><hi>sanvar</hi> for <hi>saṃvar</hi>; <hi>wantarwameṃ</hi> for <hi>wäntarwameṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="lingcomment"><hi>wantarwameṃ</hi> sic! for <hi>wäntarwameṃ</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 9 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="lingcomment">Mistaken <hi>wasaṃtpātäpi</hi> for <hi>wasaṃtpātäṣṣepi</hi>; <hi>yarpontse</hi> for <hi>yärpontse</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="lingcomment"><hi>wasaṃtpātäpi</hi> sic! and to be corrected to <hi>wasaṃtpātäṣṣepi</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 7 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="lingcomment"><hi>pkelyñe</hi> for <hi>pkelñe</hi>; <hi>kr<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>i</hi> for <hi>kwri</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="lingcomment"><hi>saṃsārṣṣa</hi> sic! and to be corrected to <hi>saṃsārṣṣana</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 11 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="lingcomment"><hi>cahhravārtti</hi> for <hi>cakravārtti</hi>; <hi>lantuñesa</hi> for <hi>lantuññesa</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 8 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 5 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment"><hi>pañäktiññe</hi> for <hi>pañäktäññe</hi>; <hi>prattika-pañäktiññe</hi> for <hi>pratika-pañäktäññe</hi>; <hi>arahanteññe</hi> for <hi>arhanteññe</hi>; <hi>ceś</hi> for <hi>k<hi rend="subscript">u</hi>ceś</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 7 akṣaras.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment">Mistaken <hi>wasaṃtpāntse</hi> for <hi>wasaṃtpātäntse</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment"><hi>cäṅken·a·</hi> is unclear.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment"><hi>saṃtpāntse</hi> sic! and to be corrected to <hi>saṃtpātäntse</hi>.</note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment" subtype="Transliteration">The gap contains about 12 akṣaras.</note></p>
